post_cb({"623903": {"ViewCount": "30856", "Body": "<p>Is there a more succinct way to define a class in a namespace than this:</p>\n<pre><code>namespace ns { class A {}; }\n</code></pre>\n<p>I was hoping something like <code>class ns::A {};</code> would work, but alas not.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "623932", "Title": "Defining a class within a namespace", "CreationDate": "2009-03-08T17:03:18.060", "LastActivityDate": "2009-03-08T22:00:19.797", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "12", "PostTypeId": "1", "OwnerDisplayName": "Iraimbilanja", "Id": "623903", "Score": "16", "Tags": "<c++><class><syntax><namespaces><definition>", "AnswerCount": "4"}, "623949": {"Id": "623949", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You can do that, but it's not really more succint.</p>\n<pre><code>namespace ns {\n    class A;\n}\n\nclass ns::A {\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>Or</p>\n<pre><code>namespace ns {\n    class B;\n}\n\nusing ns::B;\nclass B {\n};\n</code></pre>\n", "OwnerDisplayName": "Logan Capaldo", "LastActivityDate": "2009-03-08T17:24:48.663", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2009-03-08T17:24:48.663", "ParentId": "623903", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "61289"}, "623921": {"Id": "623921", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No you can't. To quote the C++ standard, section 3.3.5:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_623903_623921_0\">A name declared outside all named or\n  unnamed namespaces (7.3), blocks\n  (6.3), fun (8.3.5), function\n  definitions (8.4) and classes (clause\n  9) has global namespace scope</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So the declaration must be inside a namespace block - the definition can of course be outside it.</p>\n", "OwnerDisplayName": "anon", "LastActivityDate": "2009-03-08T17:11:02.130", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2009-03-08T17:11:02.130", "ParentId": "623903", "CommentCount": "3"}, "623937": {"Id": "623937", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The section you should be reading is this:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_623903_623937_0\"><strong>7.3.1.2 Namespace member definitions</strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_623903_623937_1\">3 Every name first declared in a namespace is a member of that namespace.[...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Note the term -- declaration so D.Shawley (and his example) is correct. </p>\n", "OwnerDisplayName": "dirkgently", "LastActivityDate": "2009-03-08T17:20:07.897", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2009-03-08T17:20:07.897", "ParentId": "623903", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "66692"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_623903_623937_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5485}}, "n3337": {"so_623903_623937_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5271}}, "n4659": {"so_623903_623937_1": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 4018}}}, "623932": {"Body": "<p>You're close, you can forward declare the class in the namespace and then define it outside if you want:</p>\n<pre><code>namespace ns {\n    class A; // just tell the compiler to expect a class def\n}\n\nclass ns::A {\n    // define here\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>What you cannot do is define the class in the namespace without members and then define the class again outside of the namespace. That violates the One Definition Rule (or somesuch nonsense).</p>\n", "CreationDate": "2009-03-08T17:15:56.750", "ParentId": "623903", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2009-03-08T22:00:19.813", "PostTypeId": "2", "LastEditorDisplayName": "EvilTeach", "LastActivityDate": "2009-03-08T22:00:19.813", "LastEditorUserId": "7734", "Id": "623932", "OwnerDisplayName": "D.Shawley", "Score": "31", "OwnerUserId": "41747"}});